"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Matthew chapters 7–8
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-matthew-7-8.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/matthew.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/matthew.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-christ/matthew.json (pre-existing: 7:24, 8:17)

Key decisions in this range:
- Sermon conclusion (7:1-27): classified as "revelation of God" for judgment/mercy passages
  and "direct" for 7:21-23 (messianic judge) and 7:28-29 (teaching with authority)
- Healing narratives (ch. 8): classified as "fulfillment" where Matthew cites Isa 53:4
  explicitly (8:17); "type" and "shadow" where healings mirror OT healing acts of God
- New Moses typology: Jesus descending the mountain (8:1) echoes Exod 34:29-32
- The centurion's faith (8:10-11): "revelation of God" — Gentile inclusion in the kingdom
- Stilling the storm (8:26): "type" — echoes Ps 107:23-30 and Jonah; divine authority over
  creation is a YHWH prerogative
- Healing of demoniacs (8:28-34): shadow — the Gadarene region and swine mirror Elijah/
  Elisha territory; authority over evil spirits is the returning dominion of the Creator
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MATTHEW = {
  "7": {
    "1": '<p>A revelation of God: "Judge not, that you be not judged" — Jesus presents the divine economy of judgment as the standard that governs his disciples\' conduct. The one who will himself judge (7:21-23; 25:31-46) is also the one who teaches mercy as the character of the kingdom. The standard "as you judge, so you will be judged" (v.2) embeds the principle that the final judgment will mirror the conduct of the one judged — a theme fully revealed in the Last Judgment discourse (25:31-46) where mercy shown to "the least of these" is mercy shown to Christ himself.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: the measure used in judgment will be applied to the judge. This principle anticipates the parables of the unmerciful servant (18:21-35) and the talents (25:14-30), where those who received mercy and hoarded it lose what they had. The Christological bearing: Christ himself embodies the ultimate mercy — receiving judgment in place of those who deserved it — which is the definitive answer to this principle rather than its circumvention.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A theme: the image of the speck and the log in the eye — the radical disproportion between perceived fault in the neighbor and actual fault in the self — recurs in the NT wisdom tradition (Rom 2:1-3; 14:10-13). Jesus is the one who sees perfectly, without the log; his judgment alone is unimpaired. The disciple\'s self-examination before judgment is a form of standing before the one who sees all things.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A theme: the rhetorical question "How can you say to your brother, \'Let me take the speck out of your eye,\' when there is the log in your own eye?" exposes the absurdity of unreformed self-appointed correction. The eschatological resonance: the one who will judge at the last day (Christ) is also the one who has removed the full weight of sin from those he saves, qualifying him alone for the role of judge.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of God: the sequence — remove the log first, then you will see clearly to remove the speck — is the order of the kingdom: transformation precedes service. The Christological application is that the disciple\'s capacity to help the neighbor flows from having been healed by Christ, not from innate moral superiority. The "clear sight" promised after self-examination points to the renewed vision the Spirit gives (John 9:39-41).</p>',
    "6": '<p>A theme: do not give dogs what is holy, nor cast pearls before pigs. The wisdom saying draws on the OT distinction between clean and unclean animals as a metaphor for the discernment of receptivity. In Matthew\'s context, this anticipates the missionary instructions of ch. 10 (shake off the dust, 10:14) and the parable of the sower (13:3-9): the gospel seed is not withheld, but the teacher must discern contexts. The holy thing entrusted to the disciples is ultimately the message of the kingdom that Christ himself embodies.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "Ask, and it will be given to you; seek, and you will find; knock, and it will be opened to you" — the promise of response to persistent prayer. The one who gives is the heavenly Father (v.11); the one who teaches this prayer is the Son who knows the Father perfectly (11:27). The prayer that avails is ultimately the prayer that aligns with the Son\'s own will — "not as I will, but as you will" (26:39). The invitation to ask is grounded in the character of the Father revealed in Christ.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: the universal promise — "everyone who asks receives, everyone who seeks finds, everyone who knocks it will be opened" — extends the invitation beyond the immediate circle. The inclusivity anticipates the Great Commission (28:19): everyone who comes, from all nations, finds the door open. The passive verbs ("will be given," "will find," "will be opened") are divine passives — the Father acts in response to the disciples\' asking.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: the analogical argument from human fatherhood to divine fatherhood — what father gives his son a stone when he asks for bread? The argument assumes that human parental love, flawed as it is, is a pale reflection of divine love. Jesus teaches the Father\'s character by analogy, and in so doing positions himself as the one who perfectly knows the Father and reveals him (11:27; John 14:9). The bread/stone contrast anticipates the temptation narrative\'s stone-to-bread offer (4:3) and the eucharistic bread.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: the fish/serpent pair in the analogical argument extends the Father\'s generosity to provision and protection. In context, the disciples are being sent as fishers of people (4:19) into hostile territory (10:16: "wise as serpents"); the Father who gives good things is also the one who protects and provides in the mission. Christ is the guarantee of this provision — he has gone before the disciples into every hostile situation.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: "If you, being evil, know how to give good gifts to your children, how much more will your Father in heaven give good things to those who ask him?" — the a fortiori argument from human to divine. Luke 11:13 replaces "good things" with "the Holy Spirit," showing the Good Thing: the ultimate gift of the Father through the Son is the Spirit. The Christological bearing is direct: Jesus is the one who will ask the Father and the Father will give the Spirit (John 14:16).</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: "So whatever you wish that others would do to you, do also to them, for this is the Law and the Prophets." The Golden Rule summarizes the whole Torah, prefacing the saying of fulfillment in 5:17 ("I came not to abolish but to fulfill"). Christ is the full embodiment of the Golden Rule: he does to others what they need, not what they deserve. The Law and Prophets finding their summary in the Golden Rule points to Christ as their fulfillment in person.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A direct teaching: "Enter by the narrow gate. For the gate is wide and the way is easy that leads to destruction, and those who enter by it are many." The narrow gate is Christ himself (John 10:9: "I am the door; if anyone enters by me, he will be saved"). The two-way motif has OT roots (Deut 30:15-19, the two ways; Ps 1:6, the way of the righteous and the way of the wicked) and is fulfilled in the person of Christ as the one way (John 14:6).</p>',
    "14": '<p>A direct teaching: "For the gate is narrow and the way is hard that leads to life, and those who find it are few." The few who find it contrasts with the many on the broad road — not a fixed predestination of quantity but a statement about the counter-intuitive nature of the kingdom way. The "hard way" is discipleship-with-Christ, which requires taking up the cross (16:24). Life (<em>zōē</em>) is the same word used in John 3:16 and 14:6 for the life Christ brings and is.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A revelation of God: "Beware of false prophets, who come to you in sheep\'s clothing but inwardly are ravenous wolves." The prophetic tradition in Israel was constantly threatened by false prophecy (Deut 13:1-5; Jer 23:9-40; Ezek 13:1-23). Jesus positions himself as the true prophet and the standard by which false prophets are tested: his fruit (life, healing, truth, the cross) defines what genuine prophetic ministry looks like. The eschatological intensification: false Christs and prophets will increase as the end approaches (24:11, 24).</p>',
    "16": '<p>A revelation of God: "You will recognize them by their fruits." The fruit test echoes Isa 5:1-7 (the vineyard that bore wild grapes instead of fruit) and anticipates the fig tree parables (21:18-22; 21:33-46). The one who brings good fruit is Christ himself — the vine that produces through his branches (John 15:5). False prophets are known by fruit; Christ is known by his fruit, and his disciples by whether they abide in him.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A theme: "Every healthy tree bears good fruit, but the diseased tree bears bad fruit." The organic connection between the tree\'s nature and its fruit is Paul\'s argument in Galatians 5 (the fruit of the Spirit vs. the works of the flesh). The Christological application: the new humanity Christ inaugurates is a new tree — the vine of which he is the stock — producing fruit that is impossible for the diseased human nature unaided by grace.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A theme: "A healthy tree cannot bear bad fruit, nor can a diseased tree bear good fruit." The impossibility argument cuts both ways: neither Christ (the good tree) nor the unreformed human nature (the diseased tree) can produce fruit contrary to their nature. This anticipates the regeneration teaching of John 3 and the Spirit\'s role in transformation. Only union with Christ — the good tree — makes good fruit possible for the disciple.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: "Every tree that does not bear good fruit is cut down and thrown into the fire." The judgment image recurs throughout the Sermon (5:22, 29-30; 7:23) and the parables (13:40-42; 25:41). John the Baptist announced this judgment (3:10: "Even now the axe is laid to the root of the trees"). Christ is both the one who bears the fire of judgment on behalf of the tree (the cross) and the one who executes final judgment (25:31-46).</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "Thus you will recognize them by their fruits." The fruit test is the hermeneutical key to prophetic discernment throughout the OT: the prophet who leads toward faithfulness to YHWH and bears the marks of genuine commission is validated; the one who leads away is false. Jesus is the definitive validation criterion — teachers who lead toward him are confirmed by their fruit; those who lead away from him are exposed by theirs.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A direct teaching: "Not everyone who says to me, \'Lord, Lord,\' will enter the kingdom of heaven, but the one who does the will of my Father who is in heaven." This verse asserts Christ\'s eschatological authority — he is the one who opens or bars entrance to the kingdom. The discernment between genuine and nominal faith is his prerogative. "The will of my Father" is ultimately revealed as trust in the Son whom the Father sent (John 6:40), making this a statement about the centrality of authentic relation to Christ.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A direct teaching: "On that day many will say to me, \'Lord, Lord, did we not prophesy in your name, and cast out demons in your name, and do many mighty works in your name?\'" — Christ is the final judge before whom all accounts are rendered. The use of his name in prophetic or miracle ministry does not automatically constitute relationship with him. The Christological weight: Christ knows his own (John 10:14); the final judgment is a disclosure of who truly knew him and was known by him, not merely a review of religious activity.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A direct teaching: "And then will I declare to them, \'I never knew you; depart from me, you workers of lawlessness.\'" The pronouncement "I never knew you" is the most severe statement of exclusion in the Gospel and uniquely Christological: the standard for eschatological inclusion is not works, religious service, or even miracles performed in Christ\'s name, but genuine mutual knowledge — "I know my own and my own know me" (John 10:14). The echo of Ps 6:8 ("Depart from me, all you workers of evil") places Christ in the position of YHWH who speaks that psalm.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A type: the wise man who built his house on the rock — "everyone who hears these words of mine and does them will be like a wise man who built his house on the rock." The rock foundation recurs at 16:18 (Peter and the church built on the rock of Christ\'s identity) and in 1 Cor 10:4 (the spiritual rock that followed Israel was Christ). The two houses — one on rock, one on sand — correspond to the two ways of 7:13-14. Christ as the rock is the Christological fulfillment of the rock of Horeb (Exod 17:6) and the cornerstone of Ps 118:22.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A theme: the foolish man who built on sand — "everyone who hears these words of mine and does not do them will be like a foolish man who built his house on the sand." The sand-builder hears but does not act; the Christological implication is that hearing Christ\'s words without obedience is the ultimate foolishness. The destruction of the sand-built house anticipates the judgment discourse of chs. 24-25 and the parable of the ten virgins — the crisis that separates those who were genuinely prepared from those who merely appeared to be.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A revelation of God: "And the rain fell, and the floods came, and the winds blew and beat against that house, and it fell, and great was the fall of it." The storm that destroys the sand-built house is a judgment image with OT roots (Ezek 13:10-16: the wall built on sand that cannot withstand the storm of divine judgment). The eschatological storm is the judgment Jesus announces as coming; the only security against it is the rock-foundation of doing his words. Christ is both the rock and the standard of judgment.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A direct teaching: "And when Jesus finished these sayings, the crowds were astonished at his teaching." The closing formula of the Sermon on the Mount — the crowds\' astonishment — echoes the people\'s response at Sinai. Moses descended with the Law given by God; Jesus taught on the mountain as the one who is God. The astonishment (<em>exeplēssonto</em>) is the response to the divine presence speaking through human form — the same word used for responses to Jesus\' authority throughout the Gospel (13:54; 19:25; 22:33).</p>',
    "29": '<p>A direct teaching: "For he was teaching them as one who had authority, and not as their scribes." The scribal teaching method (<em>kekah shemah</em> — "I have heard it said") quoted tradition and precedent; Jesus taught from his own authority (<em>exousia</em>). This is the Christological claim embedded in the form of his teaching: the one who gave the Torah at Sinai is now its authoritative interpreter and fulfiller. The Sermon\'s "But I say to you" antitheses made explicit what this verse states as the crowd\'s perception.</p>'
  },
  "8": {
    "1": '<p>A theme: "When he came down from the mountain, great crowds followed him." The descent from the mountain echoes Moses descending from Sinai (Exod 34:29-32); Moses radiated with the glory of having met God, while Jesus descended as God himself. The great crowds following him fulfill the prophetic image of the nations streaming to the mountain of the LORD (Isa 2:2-4; Mic 4:1-2) — the eschatological gathering of the nations to the mountain of divine instruction, now happening around the New Moses.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A fulfillment: "And behold, a leper came to him and knelt before him, saying, \'Lord, if you will, you can make me clean.\'" Leprosy (or skin disease — <em>tzara\'at</em>) rendered the afflicted person ritually unclean and excluded from the covenant community (Lev 13:45-46). The healing of a leper by YHWH was considered a divine prerogative — Miriam\'s healing (Num 12:10-15) and Naaman\'s (2 Kgs 5:1-14) were both presented as exceptional divine acts. Jesus healing lepers fulfills the messianic restoration in Isa 35:3-6 and his own answer to John\'s disciples (11:5: "lepers are cleansed").</p>',
    "3": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "And Jesus stretched out his hand and touched him, saying, \'I will; be clean.\' And immediately his leprosy was cleansed." The touch of a leper would render a person ritually impure; Jesus\' touch renders the leper clean. The pattern reverses the normal flow of contamination: the holy cleanses the unclean rather than the unclean contaminating the holy. This is the logic of the Incarnation itself — Christ takes on flesh and enters the realm of human sin and death without being corrupted by it, instead cleansing what he touches.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "And Jesus said to him, \'See that you say nothing to anyone, but go, show yourself to the priest and offer the gift that Moses commanded, for a proof to them.\'" The instruction to follow the Mosaic purification ritual (Lev 14:1-32) shows Jesus fulfilling rather than abolishing the Law (5:17). The phrase "for a proof to them" (<em>eis martyrion autois</em>) positions the healed man as living testimony to the messianic presence — the priests will have to render a verdict on a cleansed leper that only divine power could produce.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of God: "When he had entered Capernaum, a centurion came forward to him, appealing to him." The approach of a Roman centurion to Jesus anticipates the Gentile mission announced in 28:19 and the centurion\'s confession at the cross (27:54). That a military officer of the occupying power comes with faith and humility to the Jewish teacher from Nazareth illustrates the "first to the Jew, then to the Gentile" pattern of the Gospel — and its extension. The centurion stands at the threshold of the Gentile inclusion.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of God: "Lord, my servant is lying at home paralyzed, suffering terribly." The centurion intercedes for his slave — a posture of patron-client loyalty that Jesus will identify as surpassing anything he has seen in Israel (v.10). The Christological bearing: Christ receives intercession for the helpless; the suffering servant (the centurion\'s slave) is healed through the faith and intercession of another, mirroring the Isaianic Servant who heals through his own suffering on behalf of others (Isa 53:4-5).</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "And he said to him, \'I will come and heal him.\'" Jesus\' readiness to enter a Gentile home (which would have incurred ritual impurity) anticipates the Gentile mission and foreshadows Acts 10 (Peter and Cornelius). The simple declaration "I will come" mirrors YHWH\'s pattern of coming to save — from the descent to Egypt (Exod 3:8) to the promise of divine healing in Isa 35. The healer is now present and willing.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A direct revelation: "But the centurion replied, \'Lord, I am not worthy to have you come under my roof, but only say the word, and my servant will be healed.\'" The centurion\'s recognition that Jesus\' word is sufficient — operating at a distance without physical contact — is a recognition of divine prerogative. YHWH creates by speaking (Gen 1:3), sustains by his word (Ps 147:15-18), and heals by his word (Ps 107:20). The centurion understands more about the nature of Jesus\' authority than the crowds who followed the miracles.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: "For I too am a man under authority, with soldiers under me. And I say to one, \'Go,\' and he goes, and to another, \'Come,\' and he comes, and to my servant, \'Do this,\' and he does it." The military chain-of-command analogy identifies Jesus as one with ultimate authority — authority that creation, disease, and death obey. The centurion grasps what the disciples will articulate after the stilling of the storm (8:27): "what sort of man is this, that even winds and sea obey him?" Authority over creation is a YHWH prerogative.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A direct teaching: "When Jesus heard this, he marveled and said to those who followed him, \'Truly, I say to you, with no one in Israel have I found such faith.\'" Christ pronounces on the quality of faith from a Gentile — a judgment he alone is authorized to make. The astonishment of Jesus is the highest form of commendation in the Gospels, occurring here and at the Syrophoenician woman (15:28). The Gentile\'s faith is superior precisely because it is based on reasoning from Jesus\' authority rather than on having witnessed miracles.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "I tell you, many will come from east and west and recline at table with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob in the kingdom of heaven." The eschatological banquet with the patriarchs directly fulfills the vision of Isa 25:6-8 (the mountain feast for all peoples) and Isa 49:12 (people coming from east and west and north). The "reclining at table" anticipates the messianic banquet of 26:29 and the wedding feast of 22:1-14. Christ himself is the host and the one who sends the invitations to all nations.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A direct teaching: "While the sons of the kingdom will be thrown into the outer darkness. In that place there will be weeping and gnashing of teeth." The reversal — Gentiles at the patriarchs\' table, "sons of the kingdom" excluded — echoes the woes of Isa 65:13-15 where those who rejected YHWH are displaced by those who sought him. The "outer darkness" and "weeping and gnashing of teeth" appear throughout Matthew\'s judgment discourse; the Christological point is that the one who pronounces this verdict is the very one they rejected.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "And to the centurion Jesus said, \'Go; let it be done for you as you have believed.\' And the servant was healed at that very moment." The healing at a distance at the moment of Jesus\' word fulfills Ps 107:20 ("He sent out his word and healed them, and delivered them from their destruction"). The Christological claim in the structure of the event: YHWH heals by his word; Jesus heals by his word; the identification is made without explicit statement. The centurion\'s faith is vindicated immediately — faith in the word of Christ is not disappointed.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A shadow: "And when Jesus entered Peter\'s house, he saw his mother-in-law lying sick with a fever." The entry into a private home to heal a bedridden woman echoes Elijah\'s healing ministry within domestic settings (1 Kgs 17:17-24). Jesus\' healing ministry in homes — the primary social unit of the ancient world — shows the Incarnation touching every dimension of ordinary life. The healing of Peter\'s mother-in-law is the first miracle in a private household, and her response (she rose and served him) is the pattern of renewed life in Christ.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A shadow: "He touched her hand, and the fever left her, and she rose and served him." The laying on of hands for healing (and the immediate restoration to service) echoes Elisha\'s healing of the Shunammite\'s son (2 Kgs 4:34-36). The verb "served" (<em>diēkonei</em>) is discipleship vocabulary — the healed woman immediately becomes a servant, the pattern of those who have been touched by Christ\'s power. Service as the response to healing is the pattern of resurrection life throughout the Gospel (20:28: the Son of Man came to serve).</p>',
    "16": '<p>A fulfillment: "That evening they brought to him many who were oppressed by demons, and he cast out the spirits with a word and healed all who were sick." The healing of "all" (<em>pantas</em>) who were sick fulfills the scope of Isa 53:4 (cited in v.17) and anticipates the universal scope of the Great Commission (28:19). The casting out of demons "with a word" repeats the authority-through-speech motif: the one who creates and sustains by his word also expels the powers of darkness by his word.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A theme: "Now when Jesus saw a crowd around him, he gave orders to go over to the other side." The departure to "the other side" of the Sea of Galilee represents the first movement toward Gentile territory (Decapolis, reached in 8:28). The Christological shape of this movement: Jesus continually crosses boundaries — geographic, ethnic, purity-related — that others respect. Every crossing anticipates the ultimate boundary-crossing of death and resurrection.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: "And a scribe came up and said to him, \'Teacher, I will follow you wherever you go.\'" The scribe\'s offer of unconditional following is met with a warning rather than an invitation — Jesus tests the depth of the commitment before accepting it. This is characteristic of the Christological demand: discipleship means following into the places where Christ goes, including the place of having nowhere to lay his head (v.20), the cross, and beyond. The exchange mirrors Abraham\'s call (Gen 12:1: "go to the land I will show you").</p>',
    "20": '<p>A direct teaching: "And Jesus said to him, \'Foxes have holes, and birds of the air have nests, but the Son of Man has nowhere to lay his head.\'" The homelessness of the Son of Man is a direct Christological statement about the incarnate condition: the one through whom all things were made (John 1:3) entered the world without a permanent home in it (John 1:11: "he came to his own, and his own people did not receive him"). The title "Son of Man" here carries the Danielic weight of universal dominion alongside the humiliation of earthly sojourn.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: "Another of the disciples said to him, \'Lord, let me first go and bury my father.\'" The demand of discipleship as superior to the primary social obligation (burying one\'s father) shows Christ placing his claim above even the most sacred family duties of the ancient world. This is not callousness but the kingdom\'s priority claim: the dead burying the dead (v.22) contrasts the life of discipleship with the realm of death. Christ\'s call is a call from death to life (John 5:24-25), which is a higher urgency than the burial of the physically dead.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A direct teaching: "And Jesus said to him, \'Follow me, and leave the dead to bury their own dead.\'" The sharp demand — "follow me" in priority over "bury your father" — establishes Christ\'s call as the ultimate obligation, superseding all other obligations however legitimate. The Christological frame: the call to discipleship is the call to cross from death to life, and that crossing cannot be deferred. The formulation "the dead bury their own dead" implies that those outside Christ\'s life are already in the realm of death.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A type: "And when he got into the boat, his disciples followed him." The boat on the sea of Galilee becomes the arena for the revelation of Christ\'s authority over creation. The OT background: God\'s mastery over the sea is the mark of the Creator throughout the Psalms (Ps 65:7; 89:9; 107:23-30) and the prophets (Isa 51:9-10). The disciples following Jesus into the boat — as he commands the elements — mirrors the entry into the ark (Gen 7:7) and the wilderness journey: following the one who controls the waters.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A type: "And behold, there arose a great storm on the sea, so that the boat was being swamped by the waves; but he was asleep." The sleeping Jesus in the storm echoes Jonah asleep in the hold of the ship during a great storm (Jon 1:4-5) — but with the key reversal: Jonah was the cause of the storm; Jesus is the one who calms it. The Jonah typology will be made explicit in 12:39-41 ("the sign of Jonah"). The disciples\' panic contrasts with Jesus\' rest — he who has authority over the storm can sleep without fear.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A type: "And they went and woke him, saying, \'Save us, Lord; we are perishing.\'" The cry of the disciples — "Save us, Lord" (<em>sōson, Kyrie</em>) — is the language of the Psalms of lament directed to YHWH: Ps 107:28-29 ("Then they cried to the LORD in their trouble, and he delivered them from their distress. He made the storm be still, and the waves of the sea were hushed"). The disciples address Jesus with the title reserved for YHWH\'s saving acts; they cry out in exactly the right direction without yet grasping the full significance.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A direct revelation: "And he said to them, \'Why are you afraid, O you of little faith?\' Then he rose and rebuked the winds and the sea, and there was a great calm." The rebuke of wind and sea (<em>epetimēsen tois anemois kai tē thalassē</em>) uses the language of divine command over creation in the OT (Ps 104:7: "at your rebuke they flee"; Nah 1:4: "He rebukes the sea and makes it dry"). Only YHWH rebukes the sea in the OT; the disciples\' question in v.27 ("what sort of man is this?") is the right question, and the Gospel\'s answer is the Incarnation.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A direct revelation: "And the men marveled, saying, \'What sort of man is this, that even winds and sea obey him?\'" The disciples\' question identifies the event as theophanic — the OT question about extraordinary divine power placed before Jesus\' person. In Ps 107:29-31, those delivered from the storm praise YHWH; here the disciples\' praise will eventually be directed to Christ as YHWH incarnate. The question "what sort of man" (<em>potapos</em>) is the Christological question the Gospel has been building toward since the baptism (3:17: "This is my beloved Son").</p>',
    "28": '<p>A shadow: "And when he came to the other side, to the country of the Gadarenes, two demon-possessed men met him, coming out of the tombs, so that no one could pass that way." The Decapolis region (Gentile territory east of the Sea) and the dwelling-in-tombs detail establish the setting as the realm of maximum uncleanness: Gentile soil, the domain of the dead, the habitation of demonic power. Christ crossing into this territory — unasked — is the shadow of the Incarnation pattern: he enters the realm of darkness, death, and exile to restore it.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A direct revelation: "And behold, they cried out, \'What have you to do with us, O Son of God? Have you come here to torment us before the time?\'" The demons\' recognition of Jesus as "Son of God" and their reference to "the time" of judgment (the eschatological confrontation they know is coming) identifies the cosmic dimension of the exorcisms. The "time" of final judgment and the "time" of Jesus\' arrival in Gadara are related: his presence is the in-breaking of the end, a preliminary judgment that anticipates the final one. The demons know the Christological truth that the humans around Jesus are still questioning.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A shadow: "Now a herd of many pigs was feeding at some distance from them." The presence of pigs in Gentile territory marks the region as unclean within Jewish categories. The swine will become the vessel into which the demons transfer — a detail that connects to the OT imagery of impure animals as symbols of the nations estranged from God. The Gadarene scene is a miniature of the cosmic situation: the Gentile world as terrain dominated by powers hostile to God, into which the Son of God has come.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A shadow: "And the demons begged him, saying, \'If you cast us out, send us away into the herd of pigs.\'" The demonic recognition of Christ\'s authority — they must beg permission rather than resist — shows the absolute sovereignty of the Son of God over the spiritual powers. The Christological bearing: the exorcisms are preliminary victories in the cosmic war that reaches its climax at the cross and resurrection, where "the ruler of this world" is cast out (John 12:31) and the powers are disarmed (Col 2:15).</p>',
    "32": '<p>A shadow: "And he said to them, \'Go.\' So they came out and went into the pigs, and behold, the whole herd rushed down the steep bank into the sea and drowned in the waters." The expulsion of the demons and the drowning of the swine in the sea echoes the Exodus typology: Pharaoh\'s forces drowned in the sea (Exod 14:27-28) when YHWH delivered his people from demonic bondage. The sea that claims the swine (and the demons) is the same sea that Jesus just stilled — both events demonstrate sovereignty over the chaos of evil.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A revelation of God: "The herdsmen fled, and going into the city they told everything, especially what had happened to the demon-possessed men." The herdsmen\'s report to the city is the first act of proclamation in Gentile territory — a preview of the Gentile mission. The focus "especially what happened to the demon-possessed men" identifies the liberation of the demon-possessed as the central miracle: the restoration of human beings from demonic bondage to their right minds is what the Incarnation accomplishes at every level.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A revelation of God: "And behold, all the city came out to meet Jesus, and when they saw him, they begged him to leave their region." The rejection of Jesus by the Gadarenes — preferring the loss of the pigs to the presence of the Son of God — anticipates the pattern of rejection in Israel (11:20-24) and the crucifixion. The city comes out to meet him (a quasi-royal reception posture) but asks him to leave — exactly the pattern of the triumphal entry followed by the passion. The Gentiles\' rejection here is reversed at the Great Commission (28:19): the nations who refused will receive the disciples who come to them.</p>'
  }
}

